textDisplay:
Take the process of elimination approach. Always make one change at a time before testing. This is my take:
Objective: determine if those 2 high spots are inherent to the burr or if it's an external factor; if it's an external factor, what can you do to trouble shoot what it is. if it's related to the burrs themselves, what can you do, if anything? 

Get a microfiber cloth and thoroughly clean all relevant elements. 

Use sensitive calipers to measure the thickness of the high and low spots, see if there's and variation.

Mark where these 2 high spots are on the burr with a sharpie. Try rotating the burrs to a new position on either the carrier or the inner chamber and screw them in and see if the high spots change. 

Try swapping the burrs after if nothing. 
-------------------------If high spots remain, there is a manufacturing inconsistency that you'll have to live with? You could upgrade from your Turkish burrs to SPP burrs if you 
really want excellent. 

use a powered drill to speed up the process of repeatedly removing the face plate.

Objective: determine if those 2 high spots are inherent to the burr or if it's an external factor; if it's an external factor, what can you do to trouble shoot what it is. if it's related to the burrs themselves, what can you do, if anything? 

Get a microfiber cloth and thoroughly clean all relevant elements. 

Use sensitive calipers to measure the thickness of the high and low spots, see if there's and variation.

Mark where these 2 high spots are on the burr with a sharpie. Try rotating the burrs to a new position on either the carrier or the inner chamber and screw them in and see if the high spots change. 

Try swapping the burrs after if nothing. 
-------------------------If high spots remain, there is a manufacturing inconsistency that you'll have to live with? You could upgrade from your Turkish burrs to SPP burrs if you 
really want excellent. 

use a powered drill to speed up the process of repeatedly removing the face plate.
comment:
Take the process of elimination approach. Always make one change at a time before testing. This is my take:
Objective: determine if those 2 high spots are inherent to the burr or if it's an external factor; if it's an external factor, what can you do to trouble shoot what it is. if it's related to the burrs themselves, what can you do, if anything? 

Get a microfiber cloth and thoroughly clean all relevant elements. 

Use sensitive calipers to measure the thickness of the high and low spots, see if there's and variation.

Mark where these 2 high spots are on the burr with a sharpie. Try rotating the burrs to a new position on either the carrier or the inner chamber and screw them in and see if the high spots change. 

Try swapping the burrs after if nothing. 
-------------------------If high spots remain, there is a manufacturing inconsistency that you'll have to live with? You could upgrade from your Turkish burrs to SPP burrs if you 
really want excellent. 

use a powered drill to speed up the process of repeatedly removing the face plate.

textDisplay: Thank you for sharing! I got a used one from eBay for only $15 with original manual and package! However, I didn't use hot water when I tested it, and the coffee was like room temperature. At that time I assumed that the safety valve or the rubber gasket had leakage, and just the replaced it with my 2-cups Bialetti boiler (it does fit). The coffee was warm and tasted wonderful (smoother and less burnt smell than regular mocha). My Gemini comes with a extra reducer filer and I use it every time. Next time Will try to use hot water to start with. This is a very smart, 70s and timeless design but surprisingly underrepresented.
textOriginal: Thank you for sharing! I got a used one from eBay for only $15 with original manual and package! However, I didn't use hot water when I tested it, and the coffee was like room temperature. At that time I assumed that the safety valve or the rubber gasket had leakage, and just the replaced it with my 2-cups Bialetti boiler (it does fit). The coffee was warm and tasted wonderful (smoother and less burnt smell than regular mocha). My Gemini comes with a extra reducer filer and I use it every time. Next time Will try to use hot water to start with. This is a very smart, 70s and timeless design but surprisingly underrepresented.
comment: Thank you for sharing! I got a used one from eBay for only $15 with original manual and package! However, I didn't use hot water when I tested it, and the coffee was like room temperature. At that time I assumed that the safety valve or the rubber gasket had leakage, and just the replaced it with my 2-cups Bialetti boiler (it does fit). The coffee was warm and tasted wonderful (smoother and less burnt smell than regular mocha). My Gemini comes with a extra reducer filer and I use it every time. Next time Will try to use hot water to start with. This is a very smart, 70s and timeless design but surprisingly underrepresented.
